a healthy control?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lower colloid pressure and lower GFR in burns; higher colloid pressure and lower GFR in diarrhoea","Lower colloid pressure and lower GFR in burns; lower colloid pressure and lower GFR in diarrhoea","Higher colloid pressure and higher GFR in burns; higher colloid pressure and higher GFR in diarrhoea","Lower colloid pressure and higher GFR in burns; higher colloid pressure and lower GFR in diarrhoea","Higher colloid pressure and lower GFR in burns; lower colloid pressure and higher GFR in diarrhoea"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cstrong\u003Esevere burns\u003C/strong\u003E, protein loss through damaged skin leads to decreased plasma colloid osmotic pressure. Combined with fluid loss, this results in decreased blood volume and reduced GFR.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cstrong\u003Edehydrating diarrhoea\u003C/strong\u003E, fluid loss exceeds solute loss, leading to haemoconcentration and increased plasma colloid osmotic pressure. However, the significant volume depletion causes reduced renal perfusion and decreased GFR.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other combinations are incorrect: \u003Cstrong\u003Elower colloid pressure and lower GFR in both conditions\u003C/strong\u003E fails to account for haemoconcentration in diarrhoea; \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigher colloid pressure and higher GFR in both\u003C/strong\u003E contradicts the pathophysiology; \u003Cstrong\u003Elower colloid pressure and higher GFR in burns\u003C/strong\u003E misunderstands the effect of hypovolemia; and \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigher colloid pressure in burns\u003C/strong\u003E contradicts the protein loss that occurs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Severe burns decrease plasma colloid osmotic pressure and GFR due to protein loss and hypovolemia","Dehydrating diarrhoea increases plasma colloid osmotic pressure but decreases GFR due to volume depletion"],"references":["Cartotto R, Greenhalgh D. Colloids in Acute Burn Resuscitation. Crit Care Clin. 2016 Oct;32(4):507-23. doi: 10.1016/j.ccc.2016.06.002. PMID: 27600123.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51294"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15021"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51294"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-27T11:37:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T11:37:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7709"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65849"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}}